# Windsurf Rules Configuration

This project is a browser extension that removes any time-wasters from your browser history and tabs, and get you ready to work.

It is built using Plasmo, a framework for building browser extensions.
It's meant to run on Chrome.

It uses MUI for styling, Redux for state management, and React for the UI.

## Allowed File Types
- `.ts` - TypeScript files
- `.tsx` - TypeScript React components
- `.js` - JavaScript files
- `.json` - Configuration and data files
- `.md` - Documentation files
- `.html` - HTML templates
- `.css` - Stylesheets

## Excluded Directories
- `node_modules/` - Dependencies
- `.git/` - Version control
- `dist/` - Distribution builds
- `build/` - Build artifacts

## Special Directories
- `docs/` - Documentation
- `assets/` - Public assets
- `static/` - Static assets
- `views/` - Views
- `lib/` - Library code
- `components/` - Components
- `hooks/` - Hooks
- `store/` - Store (Redux) files
- `utils/` - Utilities
- `types/` - Types
- `constants.ts` - Constants
- `manifest.json` - Manifest file
- `tsconfig.json` - TypeScript configuration file
- `background.ts` - Background script

## Formatting
- **Auto Format on Save**: Enabled
- **Line Ending**: LF (Unix style)
- **Indent Size**: 2 spaces
- **Use Tabs**: Disabled (spaces preferred)
- Enforce consistent formatting
- Maintain readable code structure
- Use descriptive variable and function names

## Browser Extension Development
- Focus on TypeScript and React components
- Maintain clean separation between UI and logic
- Follow Chrome extension manifest v3 standards
- Use TypeScript for all code
- Use React for the UI
- Use Redux for state management
- Use MUI for styling
- Use Plasmo for building the extension
- Make sure to keep the bundle size small when possible

## General Code Style & Formatting
- Use English for all code and documentation.
- Always declare the type of each variable and function (parameters and return value).
- Avoid using any.
- Create necessary types.
- Use JSDoc to document public classes and methods.
- Don't leave blank lines within a function.
- One export per file.

## Naming Conventions
- Use PascalCase for classes.
- Use camelCase for variables, functions, and methods.
- Use kebab-case for file and directory names.
- Use UPPERCASE_WITH_UNDERSCORES for environment variables.
- Avoid magic numbers and define constants.

## Functions & Logic
- Keep functions short and single-purpose (<20 lines).
- Avoid deeply nested blocks by:
- Using early returns.
- Extracting logic into utility functions.
- Use higher-order functions (map, filter, reduce) to simplify logic.
- Use arrow functions for simple cases (<3 instructions), named functions otherwise.
- Use default parameter values instead of null/undefined checks.
- Use RO-RO (Receive Object, Return Object) for passing and returning multiple parameters.

## Data Handling
- Avoid excessive use of primitive types; encapsulate data in composite types.
- Avoid placing validation inside functionsâ€”use classes with internal validation instead.
- Prefer immutability for data.
- Use readonly for immutable properties.
- Use as const for literals that never change.